The paper focuses on the application of multiparty session types (MPST) for verification of actor programs, which falls under the area of programming languages (cs.PL). The paper also discusses the incorporation of sessions to actors, which involves communication and coordination among multiple entities, making it relevant to distributed computing (cs.DC) and software engineering (cs.SE). The use of Scribble, a protocol description language, and the runtime verification mechanism also relate to formal methods and verification (cs.DS). Finally, the paper presents benchmark results and evaluates the applicability of the framework to specify actor interactions, which can be considered as a form of logic and verification (cs.LO).
